all the drivers,

00:46:00.480 --> 00:46:01.854
then you have all
the passengers,

00:46:01.854 --> 00:46:04.560
and you can be a monopoly.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:08.010
I guess how do you think
about what the market will

00:46:08.010 --> 00:46:09.550
look like whether you--

00:46:09.550 --> 00:46:11.820
transportation is
centralizing and what

00:46:11.820 --> 00:46:13.287
regulatory other options--

00:46:13.287 --> 00:46:15.120
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: Very
important questions.

00:46:15.120 --> 00:46:17.080
And one of the
interesting part--

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:18.870
results from the work
I do the Columbia,

00:46:18.870 --> 00:46:21.840
not only did we get this
$0.20-per-mile opportunity

00:46:21.840 --> 00:46:26.790
identified, it turns out scale
economies are reached at about

00:46:26.790 --> 00:46:30.070
10% of the miles
driven in a community.

00:46:30.070 --> 00:46:33.060
What I mean by that is if I
had a shared fleet that I was

00:46:33.060 --> 00:46:36.390
running in Ann Arbor and
I had 10% market share

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:41.210
then I went to 11%, my cost per
mile wasn't going down anymore.

00:46:41.210 --> 00:46:43.830
That suggests that
you don't need

00:46:43.830 --> 00:46:47.730
to have the entire market in
order to have scale and be

00:46:47.730 --> 00:46:48.480
competitive.

00:46:48.480 --> 00:46:51.230
With that said, there's
definitely network effects,

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:53.540
so there's definitely
scaling effects.

00:46:53.540 --> 00:46:54.690
There's learning effects.

00:46:54.690 --> 00:46:56.640
I talk about having the
world's best driver.

00:46:56.640 --> 00:46:58.620
One of the best
ways to do that is

00:46:58.620 --> 00:47:00.870
to be learning from more
and more and more vehicles

00:47:00.870 --> 00:47:02.580
on the road every day.

00:47:02.580 --> 00:47:04.940
And when-- the beauty
of a driverless car

00:47:04.940 --> 00:47:08.179
is when I learn
something from one car,

00:47:08.179 --> 00:47:10.470
I can put it in all the other
cars and make all of them

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:11.610
safer.

00:47:11.610 --> 00:47:13.920
When I learn something as
a human driver about how

00:47:13.920 --> 00:47:15.870
to do something better,
I have no mechanism

00:47:15.870 --> 00:47:17.940
for transferring that
to other human drivers.

00:47:17.940 --> 00:47:19.660
So these things
are real important,

00:47:19.660 --> 00:47:21.660
and I think they're going
to have to be watched.

00:47:21.660 --> 00:47:23.570
Certainly not a reason
not to go forward

00:47:23.570 --> 00:47:26.340
but they're going to have
to be managed for sure.

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:26.900
Over here.

00:47:26.900 --> 00:47:27.130
Yes.

00:47:27.130 --> 00:47:27.590
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:47:27.590 --> 00:47:28.090
Hi.

00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:30.330
I'm very excited
about driverless cars,

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.840
and certainly there's
tremendous future.

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.550
There's one thing that
worries me about--

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:37.000
its impact on freedom--

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:41.730
because car was the
greatest vehicle

00:47:41.730 --> 00:47:44.160
for freedom and opportunity.

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:49.960
Ability to go someplace is
a great boon for humans.

00:47:49.960 --> 00:47:53.760
But now the way the driverless
cars are being actual

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:57.600
designed and implemented means
we depend on cloud services

00:47:57.600 --> 00:48:01.110
and on provider
of cloud services

00:48:01.110 --> 00:48:04.560
desire to enable my trip.

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:08.480
Google decides not
to map certain area,

00:48:08.480 --> 00:48:12.540
the cars will not
go to that area.

00:48:12.540 --> 00:48:14.820
Google or better yet
the government decides

00:48:14.820 --> 00:48:19.710
that certain event is
not good, they can easily

00:48:19.710 --> 00:48:24.300
make cars not go to that event.

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:27.462
And this is because
we have no other way

00:48:27.462 --> 00:48:29.670
of doing things other than
through the cloud service.

00:48:32.410 --> 00:48:38.790
We will not really own anything
even if we buy the car.

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:41.364
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: Yeah.

00:48:41.364 --> 00:48:42.780
First of all, the
title of my book

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:45.030
is "Autonomy" because I
believe this future is

00:48:45.030 --> 00:48:47.260
going to bring more freedom.

00:48:47.260 --> 00:48:48.690
There's a lot of
people today that

00:48:48.690 --> 00:48:52.200
can't benefit from owning
and operating an automobile.

00:48:52.200 --> 00:48:53.450
They're too young to drive it.

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:54.490
They're too old.

00:48:54.490 --> 00:48:56.790
They're not capable
physically to do it.

00:48:56.790 --> 00:48:58.230
They can't afford it.

00:48:58.230 --> 00:48:59.195
Whatever it might be.

00:48:59.195 --> 00:49:01.320
So we really think were
going to bring more freedom

00:49:01.320 --> 00:49:03.430
to a lot more people with this.

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:06.090
If the concern that you
raise, which is really

00:49:06.090 --> 00:49:08.585
my area of expertise, if
you're concerned about that,

00:49:08.585 --> 00:49:10.710
I'd encourage you to go
out and start working on it

00:49:10.710 --> 00:49:14.580
because we want this to be an
enabler of much greater freedom

00:49:14.580 --> 00:49:17.126
rather than a
constraint or a freedom.

00:49:17.126 --> 00:49:19.500
I think when you look at the
100-year history of the auto

00:49:19.500 --> 00:49:22.136
industry, a lot of that stuff
was playing out as well.

00:49:22.136 --> 00:49:23.760
Where were you going
to build the road,

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:25.480
and we're going to
build a parking lot?

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:28.510
And who pays for the
roads and all of that?

00:49:28.510 --> 00:49:31.950
And I think we have
created an extensive amount

00:49:31.950 --> 00:49:37.740
of uneven access and inequality
in our mobility systems.

00:49:37.740 --> 00:49:41.040
I live north of Detroit, and
our neighborhoods in Detroit

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:43.110
still have a lot of poverty.

00:49:43.110 --> 00:49:45.450
And these people can't break
out of the cycle of poverty

00:49:45.450 --> 00:49:47.190
because we don't have
any transportation

00:49:47.190 --> 00:49:48.530
alternatives other than a car.

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:50.250
And the car insurance
is off the chart.

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:51.190
It's expensive.

00:49:51.190 --> 00:49:54.510
So all of this has to be
managed and talked about.

00:49:54.510 --> 00:49:56.580
And I'd encourage the
dialogue to continue.

00:49:56.580 --> 00:49:58.790
I think great observation.

00:49:58.790 --> 00:49:59.470
Yes.

00:49:59.470 --> 00:50:00.210
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:50:00.210 --> 00:50:03.120
I was wondering if you thought
that the influx of autonomous

00:50:03.120 --> 00:50:06.750
vehicles in cities will
result in cities becoming

00:50:06.750 --> 00:50:10.240
more multimodal, more walkable,
more bikable, more mass

00:50:10.240 --> 00:50:13.090
transit with first, last mile
or if you thought it would just

00:50:13.090 --> 00:50:15.910
increase car dependence,
increase the widening of roads,

00:50:15.910 --> 00:50:16.750
et cetera.

00:50:16.750 --> 00:50:19.390
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: I think
it's going to be the former.

00:50:19.390 --> 00:50:21.520
There's three parking
spaces dedicated

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:23.170
to every car in
the United States,

00:50:23.170 --> 00:50:25.270
and there's 250 million cars.

00:50:25.270 --> 00:50:29.110
So that's a lot of
parking, and that parking

00:50:29.110 --> 00:50:31.770
constrains densification.

00:50:31.770 --> 00:50:33.820
I do want to make
a point though.

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:36.550
Only 26% of Americans
live in cities.

00:50:36.550 --> 00:50:39.480
Fifty-three percent of
Americans live in suburbs.

00:50:39.480 --> 00:50:42.876
And that parking issue is
even more severe there.

00:50:42.876 --> 00:50:44.950
I'm on the board of a
real estate development

00:50:44.950 --> 00:50:47.410
company in Florida, and
we had a parcel of land

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:51.760
that we were developing along
I-75 south of Tampa, St.

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:53.680
Petersburg.

00:50:53.680 --> 00:51:00.370
And they ended up putting
a Walmart on that site.

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:02.050
But the amount of
land for parking

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:05.000
was twice the amount of
land for the building.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:06.020
And this is nuts.

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:08.380
And so I think this
is an opportunity

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:10.610
to really drive densification.

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:14.320
And secondly the vehicles
are dramatically better

00:51:14.320 --> 00:51:17.980
at detecting pedestrians,
detecting bicyclists,

00:51:17.980 --> 00:51:21.070
and taking a lot of the
risk out of the system

00:51:21.070 --> 00:51:23.680
for vulnerable roadway users.

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:26.030
I sometimes talk about
this con-- for the concept

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:27.190
of the secondhand smoke.

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:29.080
I like to talk about
secondhand physics.

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:32.110
For some reason, there's a
belief that somebody can drive

00:51:32.110 --> 00:51:35.770
a 5,000-pound Cadillac
Escalade on one of the streets

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:39.370
in Manhattan and go 45
miles an hour, and it's--

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:41.550
that's second hand physics.

00:51:41.550 --> 00:51:42.697
It's just kinetic energy.

00:51:42.697 --> 00:51:44.030
So we've got to work through it.

00:51:44.030 --> 00:51:45.520
But I'm in the
camp where I think

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:47.020
we're going to make
cities more livable,

00:51:47.020 --> 00:51:48.728
but very importantly,
I think we're going

00:51:48.728 --> 00:51:50.245
to improve suburbs a lot, too.

00:51:50.245 --> 00:51:53.110
AUDIENCE: So the whole
driverless car thing seems--

00:51:53.110 --> 00:51:55.835
reminds me a lot of the
internet in the 1980s, 1990s

00:51:55.835 --> 00:51:56.960
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: It does.

00:51:56.960 --> 00:51:59.050
AUDIENCE: A lot of
innovation, exciting things.

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:01.990
One of the things that happened
after that time in the internet

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:07.365
is we discovered there's a
lot of malefactors out there.

00:52:07.365 --> 00:52:10.690
And one of the things that
I haven't heard anyone

00:52:10.690 --> 00:52:12.610
in this industry really
talking about too much

00:52:12.610 --> 00:52:19.660
is how do you defend and
make secure your driverless

00:52:19.660 --> 00:52:22.330
car not only against the kind
of attacks that are already

00:52:22.330 --> 00:52:27.310
taking place against
automated but driver-full cars

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:31.120
but against jamming or other
kinds of attacks on the sensors

00:52:31.120 --> 00:52:35.025
and things like that, which
nobody's doing that now.

00:52:35.025 --> 00:52:35.650
It's wonderful.

00:52:35.650 --> 00:52:39.840
Everybody's cooperating mostly,
but that doesn't last forever.

00:52:39.840 --> 00:52:40.840
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: Yeah.

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:42.060
Yeah.

00:52:42.060 --> 00:52:46.120
The whole cyber security area,
again, is not my expertise.

00:52:46.120 --> 00:52:49.166
I talk to people who
understand it better than I do.

00:52:49.166 --> 00:52:51.290
And we've got a lot of
people working on that hard.

00:52:51.290 --> 00:52:54.100
It's not an issue that's
unique to driverless cars.

00:52:54.100 --> 00:52:56.380
It also exists in
human-driven cars.

00:52:56.380 --> 00:53:00.200
Our current curves are very
vulnerable to being hacked.

00:53:00.200 --> 00:53:02.500
It's part of the
other systems we

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:04.420
use in our daily
lives, the airline

00:53:04.420 --> 00:53:05.740
system and other things.

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:11.020
And so I share the
concern, but not to--

00:53:11.020 --> 00:53:13.204
and I'm not implying
you're suggesting this--

00:53:13.204 --> 00:53:14.620
but not to the
point where it says

00:53:14.620 --> 00:53:17.950
we shouldn't be pushing
this opportunity to it's

00:53:17.950 --> 00:53:18.920
full extent.

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:22.390
I believe the way to go
at this is to think big.

00:53:22.390 --> 00:53:24.310
And certainly Google
Self-driving Cars

00:53:24.310 --> 00:53:26.110
and Google and
Alphabet are thinking

00:53:26.110 --> 00:53:27.490
very big in this space.

00:53:27.490 --> 00:53:30.850
Start small-- 13 Priuses
get out and start learning

00:53:30.850 --> 00:53:32.980
on public roads, learn fast.

00:53:32.980 --> 00:53:35.520
We've been learning fast
now for almost a decade,

00:53:35.520 --> 00:53:38.140
and it's been
extraordinary insights.

00:53:38.140 --> 00:53:40.241
And then scale smart.

00:53:40.241 --> 00:53:41.740
I don't think
anyone's going to want

00:53:41.740 --> 00:53:44.200
to scale a system that
has the vulnerabilities

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:46.000
that you're concerned with.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:47.950
We're going to have to
have solutions to that.

00:53:47.950 --> 00:53:50.410
Should that be the
first problem to fix?

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:51.610
I don't know.

00:53:51.610 --> 00:53:55.870
I don't think solving snowstorms
on Loveland Pass at night time

00:53:55.870 --> 00:53:58.300
was the first thing to
work on on driverless cars.

00:53:58.300 --> 00:53:59.710
We may never solve that one.

00:53:59.710 --> 00:54:01.690
But I think we got to
get out there and learn.

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:02.575
So one more question.

00:54:02.575 --> 00:54:03.950
JEREMY HYLTON:
One more question.

00:54:03.950 --> 00:54:05.550
LAWRENCE D. BURNS:
One more please.

00:54:05.550 --> 00:54:10.000
AUDIENCE: So just where does
it start in a big way I mean?

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:13.960
Of course, it makes sense
to focus on the desired end

00:54:13.960 --> 00:54:18.170
state of changing the car
experience for Americans.

00:54:18.170 --> 00:54:22.240
But does it actually start
in some more limited domain?

00:54:22.240 --> 00:54:23.957
I don't know,
long-haul trucking or--

00:54:23.957 --> 00:54:25.290
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: Yes, it does.

00:54:25.290 --> 00:54:27.340
AUDIENCE: Enthusiasts,
early adopters,

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:30.850
or city centers where
there's restricted access

00:54:30.850 --> 00:54:32.564
for other kind of
vehicles or what?

00:54:32.564 --> 00:54:34.480
LAWRENCE D. BURNS: I
think those use cases are

00:54:34.480 --> 00:54:36.520
very exciting places to start--

00:54:36.520 --> 00:54:41.007
gated communities, campuses,
low-speed applications.

00:54:41.007 --> 00:54:43.090
The interesting thing about
over-the-road trucking

00:54:43.090 --> 00:54:46.550
is not all freeway links
are created the same.

00:54:46.550 --> 00:54:53.410
Some are flat, straight, nice
weather, low-traffic density,

00:54:53.410 --> 00:54:55.810
much easier to get
started with his business

00:54:55.810 --> 00:54:59.020
than some of the curvier
higher-traffic areas.

00:54:59.020 --> 00:55:02.500
So it's not going to be just
we suddenly take and deploy it

00:55:02.500 --> 00:55:05.050
on a large scale in a
major metropolitan area.

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:07.970
I think you're going to see a
whole bunch of these smaller

00:55:07.970 --> 00:55:10.880
plays done as we work hard.

00:55:10.880 --> 00:55:13.410
Again, no one's saying we're
ready to commercialize this

00:55:13.410 --> 00:55:14.660
at scale.

00:55:14.660 --> 00:55:18.080
What we are saying is we believe
the technology is reaching

00:55:18.080 --> 00:55:20.720
a point where there's
commercial-- consumer value

00:55:20.720 --> 00:55:22.170
to be had.

00:55:22.170 --> 00:55:24.769
And I think with any startup,
you want to get to that point.

00:55:24.769 --> 00:55:26.060
You want to get real customers.

00:55:26.060 --> 00:55:27.920
You want to get real
money coming in.

00:55:27.920 --> 00:55:30.630
That's what we're doing
the business to do.

00:55:30.630 --> 00:55:34.745
But I think these opportunities
you talk about are there.

00:55:34.745 --> 00:55:36.110
JEREMY HYLTON: All right, great.

00:55:36.110 --> 00:55:36.770
Thanks so much.

00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:37.340
LAWRENCE D. BURNS:
Thanks everybody.

00:55:37.340 --> 00:55:38.298
I really appreciate it.

00:55:38.298 --> 00:55:40.690
[APPLAUSE]

